---
import { caseStages, historicLessons, roadmap } from '../data/siteContent';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const corruptionDefinition = [
  'Entrusted power or controlled decision point: at least one actor is using a public, fiduciary, or institutional role that is supposed to be exercised on behalf of others.',
  'Collusion or coordinated exchange: corruption usually involves two or three actors, or a small ring, aligning benefits, protection, access, or favorable decisions rather than a lone bad act in isolation.',
  'Diffuse externalized harm: the upside is concentrated among participants while the downside is pushed onto taxpayers, consumers, shareholders, workers, pension beneficiaries, ratepayers, voters, or other unconsenting third parties.',
];

const safeguards = [
  'Structured case scoping around a defendant, conduct, and time-window triple',
  'Evidence floors before a case can gather momentum',
  'Identity verification and anti-bot controls for supporters',
  'Randomized stage-by-stage reviewer assignment',
  'Escrow rules that constrain how case funds are used',
  'Supermajority decision rules instead of bare-majority judgment',
];

const usModel = [
  'Sliding filing tiers that let an initial plaintiff choose the signature and funding target up front',
  'Per-case escrow and clearly defined refund, cost, and reserve logic',
  'A standing pool of at least 1,000 qualified judges or legal reviewers',
  'A 15-juror trial panel with 12 of 15 required to convict',
  'Remedies centered on damages, disgorgement, public findings, referrals, and role ineligibility rather than assumed criminal sentencing power',
];

const homeHref = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="USACC Framework"
  description="A public brief translating the anti-corruption court concept into a framework centered on collusion, diffuse externalized harm, and strong procedural safeguards."
>
  <header class="subpage-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <a class="back-link" href={homeHref}>Back to home</a>
      <p class="section-kicker">Framework Brief</p>
      <h1>A working public brief for the US Anti-Corruption Court concept.</h1>
      <p class="lede narrow">
        This page condenses the provided whitepaper and draft plan into a clearer public-facing
        narrative. It preserves the main design logic while foregrounding the recurring pattern
        of collusion plus diffuse externalized cost, and staying explicit that the project is
        still exploratory and nonprofit-oriented.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <main>
    <section class="section">
      <div class="container article-shell">
        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">Why this exists</p>
          <h2>Corruption often falls into a standing gap because the benefits are concentrated and the negative effects are diffuse.</h2>
          <p>
            The materials behind USACC argue that many serious corruption patterns are not random
            single-actor abuses. They are collusive arrangements in which a small number of
            participants trade favors, protection, access, or money while the losses are shifted
            onto taxpayers, consumers, ratepayers, pension beneficiaries, workers, or voters.
            The harm is real, but it is diffuse enough that the public rarely appears as a
            plaintiff in a form conventional systems can process cleanly.
          </p>
          <p>
            The concept therefore explores a parallel intake, review, and adjudication structure
            that can hear higher-signal claims without depending on political permission or a
            single directly injured claimant with large individual damages. That is also where the
            case for public intervention is strongest: externalities are precisely the domain in
            which private bargains fail, whether the example is pollution, procurement steering,
            or a captured regulatory decision that burdens people outside the arrangement.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">Scope</p>
          <h2>What counts as corruption in this model.</h2>
          <ul class="article-list">
            {corruptionDefinition.map((item) => (
              <li>{item}</li>
            ))}
          </ul>
          <p>
            The draft also explicitly includes conduct that is blatant and corrosive even when it
            is structured to stay technically inside current law. That includes regulatory
            capture, revolving-door rewards, procurement steering, pension self-dealing,
            disclosure laundering, and insider dealing by public servants. The common thread is
            not just bad behavior. It is a compact set of actors coordinating upside while pushing
            risk, loss, or exclusion onto people outside the deal, including people who may not
            even realize they are the ones absorbing the cost.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">Expandable Brief</p>
          <h2>Why “diffuse negative effects” matters.</h2>
          <div class="expand-stack">
            <details class="expand-card" open>
              <summary>Diffuse does not just mean “big.”</summary>
              <p>
                A harm can be enormous and still easy to litigate if one plaintiff clearly bears
                it. Diffuse harm is different: the loss is scattered across many people, so each
                person carries too little of the total burden to justify a full legal fight alone.
              </p>
            </details>

            <details class="expand-card">
              <summary>Pollution is the easiest analogy.</summary>
              <p>
                Pollution works because an actor can keep the upside of production while
                offloading the cleanup cost, health burden, or environmental damage onto the
                public. The court concept treats many corruption schemes as structurally similar:
                a compact deal on one side, diffuse negative effects on the other.
              </p>
            </details>

            <details class="expand-card">
              <summary>Victims may be unknowing, indirect, or spread out.</summary>
              <p>
                The people paying the price may be ratepayers, taxpayers, pension beneficiaries,
                workers, consumers, or residents who never saw the underlying arrangement and may
                not know why they are worse off. That is exactly why ordinary standing often
                breaks down.
              </p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">Case Flow</p>
          <h2>The four-stage architecture.</h2>
          <div class="article-stage-grid">
            {caseStages.map((stage) => (
              <section class="article-stage">
                <p class="card-kicker">{stage.eyebrow}</p>
                <h3>{stage.title}</h3>
                <p>{stage.body}</p>
                <ul class="article-list">
                  {stage.bullets.map((bullet) => (
                    <li>{bullet}</li>
                  ))}
                </ul>
              </section>
            ))}
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">Safeguards</p>
          <h2>How the proposal tries not to become a political weapon.</h2>
          <ul class="article-list">
            {safeguards.map((item) => (
              <li>{item}</li>
            ))}
          </ul>
          <p>
            The recurring design principle is that public participation is valuable only when it
            is paired with friction, verification, and independent review. The project’s theory
            of legitimacy depends as much on distinguishing collusion from mere incompetence or
            policy disagreement as it does on what the system ultimately hears.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">U.S. Draft</p>
          <h2>What the newer anti-corruption court plan adds.</h2>
          <ul class="article-list">
            {usModel.map((item) => (
              <li>{item}</li>
            ))}
          </ul>
          <p>
            This draft makes the adjudication mechanics more concrete. Instead of gesturing
            toward abstract review, it sketches a large standing judge pool, a 15-person panel,
            explicit conviction math, escrow-backed case funding, and a remedy model that stays
            realistic about what a nonprofit or court-adjacent body could actually enforce while
            keeping the record focused on who coordinated, who benefited, and who absorbed the
            diffuse cost.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">Historical lessons</p>
          <h2>What earlier anti-corruption bodies teach.</h2>
          <div class="card-grid two-up">
            {historicLessons.map((lesson) => (
              <section class="mini-card">
                <h3>{lesson.title}</h3>
                <p>{lesson.body}</p>
              </section>
            ))}
          </div>
          <p>
            The combined lesson is straightforward: independence, scope discipline, and
            distributed decision-making matter more than heroic personalities. Anti-corruption
            bodies that depend on political goodwill usually lose that goodwill as soon as they
            start to matter.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">Next steps</p>
          <h2>What this project needs before it becomes more than a concept note.</h2>
          <ol class="article-list article-list-numbered">
            {roadmap.map((item) => (
              <li>{item}</li>
            ))}
          </ol>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
